There is still the missing feature of adding the number of downstream files for each entry of the report, but I'll leave that to a later PR, since I am not yet happy with what I have.

I think but I'm not 100% sure this can be deleted:
```suggestion
```

I think in the main CI workflow jq is only used in `lean-pr-testing-comments.sh`. Note to self: if true, it would be good to document that.
I am going to test the removal in #18636, once it is done doing its "full run".
I think that the test was successful: this step is not needed if you just want to build mathlib.
Just to check my understanding: because of this option, getting the cache with lake would be useless, right?

Yes, if the cache was available, `lake build` would replay it, since setting options on the command line does not seem to trigger a rebuild.  Moreover, once you modify the `lakefile`, everything has to be rebuild.
Perhaps it would be good to leave comments in files that are touched here so that if someone edits these lines, they'll know to fix this workflow step?

I added a comment to the lakefile in the test PR and I'll merge once testing is complete.

Rather than commenting on the remaining two files, I added a test run of `lake build Mathlib.Init` that should give further indication if something goes wrong.
Work into here the refence commit hash and post it to Zulip.
Same schedule as the Technical Debts Counter: is this ok?
It should be fine, the Technical Debts Counter doesn't use a Hoskinson runner and also takes much less time than this job anyways.
Could you add a cleanup step to delete any files created by this build so that they don't accumulate on the Hoskinson runners?
Actually, I guess this isn't necessary because the first cleanup step already nukes everything?
I think that's right: the cleanup step is in the main CI and I simply copied it over.

Cf. #15996 
```suggestion

# Make this script robust against unintentional errors.
# See e.g. http://redsymbol.net/articles/unofficial-bash-strict-mode/ for explanation.
set -euo pipefail
IFS=$'\n\t'

```
Thanks!
